    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="1071"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1071">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/3770.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Consul
                            <persName type="to">Canada</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 24, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Contents your April 24, 10 a.m., were conveyed to the British Ambassador here. He
                    immediately offered to cable the British Minister at Mexico to make
                    representations in behalf of all the foreigners involved, and suggests that if
                    you will give all information involving possible loss of human life direct to
                    the British Admiral at Veracruz, he will instruct the Admiral to take all
                    necessary steps looking to a solution of each case. In this way time will be
                    saved. Copy of what goes to the British Admiral should be forwarded to the
                    British Consul at Veracruz.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
